(630, 8, '2008-08-11 05:00:00', '2008-08-11 04:00:00', '(<i>University of Exeter</i>) Research led by UK and Australian scientists sheds new light on the role that our ancestors played in the extinction of Australia''s prehistoric animals. Their study suggests that the mass extinction of Tasmania''s large prehistoric animals was the result of human hunting, and not climate change as previously believed.', 'New evidence implicates humans in prehistoric animal extinctions', 0, '(<i>University of Exeter</i>) Research led by UK and Australian scientists sheds new light on the role that our ancestors played in the extinction of Australia''s prehistoric animals. Their study suggests that the mass extinction of Tasmania''s large prehistoric animals was the result of human hunting, and not climate change as previously believed.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-evidence-implicates-humans-in-prehistoric-animal-extinctions', '', '', '2008-08-11 05:00:00', '2008-08-11 04:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2008-08/uoe-nei081108.php', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(631, 6, '2008-08-12 13:00:00', '2008-08-12 12:00:00', 'Scientists sheds new light on the role that our ancestors played in the extinction of Australia''s prehistoric animals. Their study suggests that the mass extinction of Tasmania''s large prehistoric animals was the result of human hunting, and not climate change as previously believed.', 'Humans Implicated In Prehistoric Animal Extinctions With New Evidence', 0, 'Scientists sheds new light on the role that our ancestors played in the extinction of Australia''s prehistoric animals. Their study suggests that the mass extinction of Tasmania''s large prehistoric animals was the result of human hunting, and not climate change as previously believed.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'humans-implicated-in-prehistoric-animal-extinctions-with-new-evidence', '', '', '2008-08-12 13:00:00', '2008-08-12 12:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2008/08/080811200028.htm', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(550, 5, '2008-08-15 09:11:11', '2008-08-15 09:11:11', 'According to Digitalspy website: &#34;The return of celebrity genealogy series Who Do You Think You Are? was ratings gold for the BBC last night (Wednesday 13 August). The first episode of a new eight-part series, which saw actress Patsy Kensit investigate her villainous ancestry, brought in 6.85m (29.9%) to BBC One in the 9pm hour. The figure is up on the 4.05m (19.1%) who watched Crimewatch in the same slot last week and is also an improvement on the 6.5m (29.5%) for the debut of the last series in September 2007.&#34; I enjoyed the programme, and as I know a bit about criminal and military records, I was particularly impressed with the research which turned up Ms Kensit''s ancestors. However, I didn''t realise how emotional genealogy is because she kept breaking into tears. Is this a regular occurence in the reading rooms?', 'Ratings gold', 0, 'According to Digitalspy website: &#34;The return of celebrity genealogy series Who Do You Think You Are? was ratings gold for the BBC last night (Wednesday 13 August). The first episode of a new eight-part series, which saw actress Patsy Kensit investigate her villainous ancestry, brought in 6.85m (29.9%) to BBC One in the 9pm hour. The figure is up on the 4.05m (19.1%) who watched Crimewatch in the same slot last week and is also an improvement on the 6.5m (29.5%) for the debut of the last series in September 2007.&#34; I enjoyed the programme, and as I know a bit about criminal and military records, I was particularly impressed with the research which turned up Ms Kensit''s ancestors. However, I didn''t realise how emotional genealogy is because she kept breaking into tears. Is this a regular occurence in the reading rooms?', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ratings-gold', '', '', '2008-08-15 09:11:11', '2008-08-15 09:11:11', '', 0, 'http://www.ancestorsmagazine.co.uk/?page=blog#104', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(549, 5, '2008-08-18 17:20:39', '2008-08-18 17:20:39', 'I was pleased to see that Saturday''s Guardian newspaper had a story based on Chris Pomery''s piece in August''s issue on the abandonment of the General Register Office''s plans to digitise the birth, marriage and death certificates at a cost of &#38;pound;16m. The Guardian story is at <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2008/aug/16/genealogy.records">http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2008/aug/16/genealogy.records</a>. Meanwhile Guy Kawaski a partner at Garage Technology Ventures, an early-stage venture capital firm, and formerly  &#34;chief evangelist of Apple&#34; (the mind boggles at the job description), has contacted me to say that this blog has been added to <a href="http://genealogy.alltop.com">http://genealogy.alltop.com</a> which is a well laid out list of mainly American genealogical blogs, which was nice. Incidentally we have a survey of genealogical blogs and podcasts in the October issue on sale on 4 September - reserve your copy now. But of course there always has to be downside. I was checking out the new search engine cuil (pronounced cool) at <a href="http://www.cuil.com">http://www.cuil.com</a> and typed in &#34;Simon Fowler&#34; as one does. The result caused consternation in the Ancestors'' office. Try it for yourself: look at the photograph next to a link to an article in Wikipedia. Joking aside it is an interesting attempt to rival Google. <br />', 'Highs and lows', 0, 'I was pleased to see that Saturday''s Guardian newspaper had a story based on Chris Pomery''s piece in August''s issue on the abandonment of the General Register Office''s plans to digitise the birth, marriage and death certificates at a cost of &#38;pound;16m. The Guardian story is at <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2008/aug/16/genealogy.records">http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2008/aug/16/genealogy.records</a>. Meanwhile Guy Kawaski a partner at Garage Technology Ventures, an early-stage venture capital firm, and formerly  &#34;chief evangelist of Apple&#34; (the mind boggles at the job description), has contacted me to say that this blog has been added to <a href="http://genealogy.alltop.com">http://genealogy.alltop.com</a> which is a well laid out list of mainly American genealogical blogs, which was nice. Incidentally we have a survey of genealogical blogs and podcasts in the October issue on sale on 4 September - reserve your copy now. But of course there always has to be downside. I was checking out the new search engine cuil (pronounced cool) at <a href="http://www.cuil.com">http://www.cuil.com</a> and typed in &#34;Simon Fowler&#34; as one does. The result caused consternation in the Ancestors'' office. Try it for yourself: look at the photograph next to a link to an article in Wikipedia. Joking aside it is an interesting attempt to rival Google. <br />', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'highs-and-lows', '', '', '2008-08-18 17:20:39', '2008-08-18 17:20:39', '', 0, 'http://www.ancestorsmagazine.co.uk/?page=blog#105', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(632, 6, '2008-08-18 19:00:00', '2008-08-18 18:00:00', 'A century-old drug, methylene blue, may be able to slow or even cure Alzheimer''s and Parkinson''s disease. Used at a very low concentration -- about the equivalent of a few raindrops in four Olympic-sized swimming pools of water -- the drug slows cellular aging and enhances mitochondrial function, potentially allowing those with the diseases to live longer, healthier lives.', 'Potential Alzheimer&#039;s, Parkinson&#039;s Cure Found In Century-old Drug', 0, 'A century-old drug, methylene blue, may be able to slow or even cure Alzheimer''s and Parkinson''s disease. Used at a very low concentration -- about the equivalent of a few raindrops in four Olympic-sized swimming pools of water -- the drug slows cellular aging and enhances mitochondrial function, potentially allowing those with the diseases to live longer, healthier lives.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'potential-alzheimers-parkinsons-cure-found-in-century-old-drug', '', '', '2008-08-18 19:00:00', '2008-08-18 18:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2008/08/080818101335.htm', 0, 'post', '', 0),
