(1634, 4, '2010-11-10 18:10:00', '2010-11-10 18:10:00', 'When you turn on the TV or open the newspaper, there doesnÃ¢Â€Â™t seem to be a day pass by, without hearing that someone has gone missing in the UK. Whether by fair means or foul, itÃ¢Â€Â™s an extremely distressing time for their families and friends and questions are always asked as to Ã¢Â€Âœwhat could I have done differently?Ã¢Â€Â<br />\n<br />\nNow, with over 11.5million* people over 18 using internet dating websites or Ã¢Â€Â˜find a friendÃ¢Â€Â™ columns in newspapers looking to meet new friends or start relationships, itÃ¢Â€Â™s even more important to let people know details about when and who you are meeting. However, telling a responsible friend what you are doing isnÃ¢Â€Â™t always easy and this is where new personal safety service <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> can help. Working with input from current and former police officers around the UK, <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> have devised the ultimate Ã¢Â€Â˜personal safety check-in serviceÃ¢Â€Â™, which is perfect for those who wish to keep their private life private, but safe at the same time.<br />\n<br />\nFor a small fee per month, your personal details are registered with the specially trained team at <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a>Ã¢Â€Â™s UK office Ã¢Â€Â“ things that would need to be given for a missing persons report such as next of kin, height, weight etc. which is then entered onto the database. This process has been designed to make it quicker to action help, in the hopefully unlikely event that it is needed. Next you supply details of your date to the system, who they are, where and when you are meeting and a time as to when you expect the date to be finished. <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> can also give you a check up call or text during the date to make sure all is OK and there will be a specially agreed panic code word you can use if you feel uncomfortable with the person youÃ¢Â€Â™re with and if you need assistance.<br />\n<br />\nShould help be needed, <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a>, acting as your designated Ã¢Â€Â˜next of kinÃ¢Â€Â™, will alert the relevant services and you can rest assured that someone knows where you are and is acting to keep you safe. Hopefully though, it will be just a case of notifying <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> that you have reached the end of your date and thatÃ¢Â€Â™s it until next time. Also, if youÃ¢Â€Â™re finding that youÃ¢Â€Â™re having a great time and want the date to go on for longer, you can always extend that too by calling or texting Ã¢Â€Â“ <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> is as flexible as you want it to be.<br />\n<br />\nUsing <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a>r there is no embarrassment that you are on a blind date or you''re with someone your family and friends might not approve of and all of the information given to <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> is confidential. Perfectly timed for the Christmas party season this new safety service is being welcomed by pubs and clubs across the East Anglia region and the <a href=''http://suzylamplugh.org'' >Suzy Lamplugh Trust</a> says Ã¢Â€Â˜the <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> concept offers a valuable addition to personal safety.Ã¢Â€Â™<br />\n<br />\nThis new service launches in East Anglia 24th November with a national roll-out Christmas 2010. <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a> - a service that never sleeps, never forgets and never loses information.<br />\n<br />\n* Figures courtesy of Dating Direct and Match.com<br />\n<br />\nAbout <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a><br />\n<br />\nFormed initially to provide a support service for individuals or groups engaged in hazardous activities where it is advisable to have someone know where you are and what you are doing, it seemed a natural fit to the dating environment. From Climbing, Sailing and Caving through to Dating - these activities advise participants to file a plan or tell someone what they are doing, but people donÃ¢Â€Â™t often get around to it. And, if they do, the individuals who have been entrusted with the information donÃ¢Â€Â™t manage it properly. Consequently when things go wrong, the rescue and emergency services are usually late in being summoned and are hampered by the lack of hard information.<br />\n<br />\nThe founder of <a href=''http://guardianstar.co.uk'' >GuardianStar</a>, Paul Dickinson and his team are all passionate about this new personal safety service and the team bring various skills and experience to the operation including Emergency Planning and Co-ordination, Emergency Services Operations, Military Expeditions (Operations and Planning), Health and Safety, Paramedic Services, Communications & Information Systems design and operation of service applications.<br />\n<br />\nThe Dating Service Module is soon to be followed by the Adventure Module in early 2011.<br />\n<br />\n<a title=''Goes&nbsp;to&nbsp;website&nbsp;of:&nbsp;www.guardianstar.co.uk'' href=''http://www.guardianstar.co.uk'' >www.guardianstar.co.uk</a><br />\n<br />\nFor more information on this new service, the opportunity to speak to founder Paul Dickinson or to test the service, please call;<br />\n<br />\nMichelle Russell <br />\ne: <a title=Sends&nbsp;email&nbsp;to:&nbsp;michellerussell href="mailto:michellerussell@meeshcomms.com">michellerussell@meeshcomms.com</a> <br />\nt: 07909 911275<br />\n - Michelle Russell 10-11-2010<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/ReleaseWireLeisureAndHobbies/~4/UfHWnH9gzRM" height="1" width="1"/>', 'Personal Safety Service Launches in UK', 0, 'When you turn on the TV or open the newspaper, there doesnÃ¢Â€Â™t seem to be a day pass by, without hearing that someone has gone missing in the UK. Whether by fair means or foul, itÃ¢Â€